                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d756">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">125.6336/11–2648: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Peiping</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clubb</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-11-26T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 26, 1948—6 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 26—8:32 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>492. Information received orally by member this office from Chinese reporter just
                    arrived Peiping from Mukden (which he left November 11) is to effect that
                    Communist authorities Mukden have placed 6 soldiers on guard before American
                    Consulate General and 2 at Consul General’s residence with presumed purpose
                    protection but actually for purpose observing their actions.</p>
                <p>Same informant stated USIS library Mukden now closed, will reopen to public by
                    December 1.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 492, repeated Nanking 731, Shanghai 483.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Clubb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
